Laches, father of Phaedria and Chaerea, is just returned from his country seat in the suburbs, and is quietly felici- tating himself on the comfort of being so near to the city that he can be there or in the country as the whim takes him. See- ing Parmeno standing at Laches’ door he questions him, and soon perceives by his confusion that there is some mischief in the wind. Parmeno in much trepidation tells him all: and Laches hurries off to the rescue, leaving Parmeno to reflect upon his own coming punishment.

The Metre is iambic trimeter.
